          "body": "Verse 5 is the chapter's most unexpected theological moment. Mid-oracle, Isaiah breaks the third-person description and inserts himself: 'My heart cries out for Moab.' This is not a scribal accident or emotional aside. It is the text's clearest signal that Isaiah's prophecy is not being delivered with detachment. He is weeping for the people he is sentencing. The same divine-human grief pattern appears in Jeremiah's weeping for Moab in Jeremiah 48:31-36, and most climactically in Jesus weeping over Jerusalem while simultaneously pronouncing its destruction (Luke 19:41-44). The pattern reveals something important about the character of the God whose oracles these are: He does not take pleasure in the death of the wicked (Ezekiel 18:23, 32; 33:11). Judgment and grief are not opposites in the biblical God. The prophet's tears are the human face of a divine sorrow — what God feels about what He must do. As Keller has observed, this is the God who is simultaneously the most just Judge who has ever lived and the one most broken by what justice requires."
